"Sancho L.G., Allan Green T.G., Pintado A.","Slowest to fastest: Extreme range in lichen growth rates supports their use as an indicator of climate change in Antarctica",2007,"Flora: Morphology, Distribution, Functional Ecology of Plants","202","8",,"667","673",,,10.1016/j.flora.2007.05.005,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-35248824541&partnerID=40&md5=ec277ac009e29063f0896723a539b8cd","Departamento de Biología Vegetal II, Facultad de Farmacia, Universidad Complutense de Madrid, 28040 Madrid, Spain; Biological Sciences, Waikato University, Hamilton, New Zealand","Sancho, L.G., Departamento de Biología Vegetal II, Facultad de Farmacia, Universidad Complutense de Madrid, 28040 Madrid, Spain; Allan Green, T.G., Departamento de Biología Vegetal II, Facultad de Farmacia, Universidad Complutense de Madrid, 28040 Madrid, Spain, Biological Sciences, Waikato University, Hamilton, New Zealand; Pintado, A., Departamento de Biología Vegetal II, Facultad de Farmacia, Universidad Complutense de Madrid, 28040 Madrid, Spain","Global temperature rise is suggested to be greater and more rapid in polar regions. There has been a clear temperature rise of 0.056 °C y-1 in the Antarctic Peninsula and this has led to changes in higher plant extent and range. In the more extreme environments of the main continent the vegetation is scattered and composed of lichens and mosses. There is interest in the possible effects of global climate change on these communities acting through changes in temperature and precipitation. Lichens have been extensively used to date the substrates on which they are growing using the techniques of lichenometry. The slow growth and longevity of lichens particularly suites them for this use. We present evidence that there appears to be a substantial (two orders of magnitude) cline in lichen growth rate from the warmer, wetter and more productive Peninsula to the cold Dry Valleys at 77°S latitude. The differences in growth rate reflect the precipitation and temperature regimes at the different sites. The large range in growth rates coupled with the simplicity of measuring lichen growth using modern techniques suggests that this could be an excellent tool for the detection of climate change in continental Antarctica. © 2007 Elsevier GmbH. All rights reserved.","Biomonitoring; Buellia; Cape Hallett; Dry Valleys; Lichenometry; Rhizocarpon","bioindicator; biomonitoring; climate change; global climate; growth rate; lichen; lichenometry; longevity; polar region; precipitation (climatology); temperature effect; vegetation; Antarctic Peninsula; Antarctica; Cape Hallett; East Antarctica; McMurdo Dry Valleys; West Antarctica; Bryophyta; Buellia; Embryophyta; Rhizocarpon",,,,,,"Armstrong, R.A., Growth curve of the lichen Rhizocarpon geographicum (1983) New Phytol., 94, pp. 619-622; Armstrong, R., Lichens, lichenometry and global warming (2004) Microbiologist, 2004, pp. 32-35; Bañón, M., El clima de las Shetland del Sur y norte de la Península Antártica (1992) La Metereología, 7-8, pp. 38-45; Bailey, D.K., Phytogeography and taxonomy of Pinus subsection Balfourianae (1970) Ann. Mo. Bot. Gard., 57, pp. 210-249; Benedict, J.B., Nash III, T.H., Radial growth and habitat selection by morphologically similar chemotypes of Xanthoparmelia (1990) Bryologist, 93, pp. 319-327; Brabyn, L., Green, T.G.A., Beard, C., Seppelt, R., GIS goes nano: vegetation studies in Victoria Land, Antarctica (2005) NZ Geogr., 61, pp. 139-147; Brock, D.H., Primary colonization of Surtsey, with special reference to the blue-green algae (1973) Oikos, 24, pp. 239-243; Bull, W.B., Dating San Andreas Fault earthquakes with lichenometry (1996) Geology, 24, pp. 111-114; Bull, W.B., Brandon, M.T., Lichen dating of earthquake-generated regional rockfall events, Southern Alps, New Zealand (1998) Geol. Soc. Am. Bull., 110, pp. 60-84; Doran, P.T., Priscu, J.C., Lyons, W.B., Walsh, J.E., Fountain, A.G., McKnight, D.M., Moorhead, D.L., Parsons, A.N., Antarctic clima